ndscapes.Traveling largely outside of cities, away from well-beaten tourist tracks, the authors cross Japan, Korea, China, Turkmenistan, Turkey, Greece, Sicily, Spain, Portugal, the Azores Islands, and the United States—from Chesapeake Bay to San Francisco Bay. The stories they gather provide stark contrasts as well as reaffirming similarities across diverse cultures. Generously illustrated with maps and photos, Traveling the 38th Parallel documents devastating environmental losses but also inspiring gains made through the efforts of dedicated individuals working against the odds to protect these fragile places.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHuman geography. 0aHydrology. 0aOceanography. 7aSCIENCE / Earth Sciences / Geography.2bisacsh  a38th north parallel.  aadventure.  aadventures.  aamericas.  aaround the world journey.  aasia.  acivilization.  aclimate.  acultural intersections.  adiverse cultures.  aearth sciences.  aeasy to read.  aengaging.  aenvironmental losses.  aenvironmental studies.  aenvironmental.  aeurope.  afragile places.  ageography.  ahabitat protection.  ahuman societies.  akorea.  alocal activists.  amiddle latitude.  anatural settings.  anature.  apark rangers.  apollution.  ariveting stories.  ascience.  atravel guides.  atravel.  aturkey.  avillages.  avoyages.  awater supply.  awetlands.  aworld history.1 aCarle, Janet, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026654440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095455740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520954557423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520954557/original  a978-3-11-069042-2